    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the goblin confusion! Let's dive into the actual process, sans the mystical creatures. When you decide to buy a house, the money involved in the transaction is quite significant. To ensure that both you and the seller are protected, an escrow account is used. Here's how it works:\n\n1. You agree to buy the house and provide a down payment to your real estate agent or directly to the seller.\n2. Your real estate agent or a designated escrow company then opens an escrow account, which is a secure account managed by a third party.\n3. The funds from your down payment are transferred to this escrow account.\n4. The seller's agent or the seller themselves will provide you with a copy of the property disclosure statement and other necessary documents.\n5. Once you review and approve these documents, the escrow company will release the funds to the seller, minus any agreed-upon closing costs or fees.\n6. The final step is the closing, where all the paperwork is signed, and the house officially changes hands.\n\nThis process ensures that the funds are only released when all the conditions of the sale are met, providing a layer of security for both parties involved. I hope this clarifies the process for you!",
